english:
  title: A Letter to the General
  author: Choe Chi-won
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I am but rotting grass with nowhere to lean, a broken tumbleweed rolling of its own accord. Though I wander far, I cannot escape the dust of this world; walking alone, I grow ever more lost at the crossroads.

    Yesterday I came bearing my utmost sincerity, rushing forth to your luminous presence, yet I trembled that my flute-song might offend and grew mournful at my own futile melodies. But you, General, remembering that I came from distant lands and labor diligently in the way of learning, have drawn me close with infinite kindness, allowing me to offer myself in service. Your teaching runs so deep that even the blind man need not stumble, and your praise of worthy words ensures no one becomes the fool who tries in vain. Yet how can I bear such undeserved honor? Your brilliance already shines to its fullest.

    I have no means to advance myself, only the wish to withdraw. I make poetry my nourishment and books my foundation. Though I have once tasted official stipends, poverty still gnaws at me—the miser's purse forever empty, the poor man's cauldron never warm. My family scattered across four provinces, our paths separated by ten states' distance: my sorrows simmer through the night, my letters arrive only after years of delay. The times grow cold and bitter, customs crude and false. Gold for laughter comes easy; grain for study comes hard. The sky is too high to question, and evening falls without direction home. Only now do I understand: a scholar's heart must depend upon the grace of the truly impartial.

    How fortunate that I have met you, my lord—a presence vast as mountains, deep as seas, with rain that nourishes and wind that carries all forth. One word of encouragement from you and the crowd takes notice; the smallest skill displayed becomes put to use according to talent. Thus nothing escapes your beautifying influence, and no common person fails to receive your profound benevolence. If all the people of the Central Kingdom receive such nurture, how could a foreign scholar alone be cast away?

    I, with my meager talents, dared cast myself upon your virtuous light, never dreaming you would deign to lift me up, to breathe life into my endeavors again and again. While others trace their fortunes to fate and their flowering or withering to destiny, mine depend entirely on your grace. Should you but lend me your powerful word, even my humble nature might be transformed to glory—as a needle finds its way through thread, as a peg discovers purchase in a bag.

    I have already leaned upon the path of office and have come to understand something of administrative ways. Should you direct my efforts, I need not hide myself away. In time, I shall achieve a household of substance, and I shall not shrink from labor in the provinces. But time flows swift and stern ambition burns hard to sustain. I seek only your shelter and protection, hoping for transformation. I wish the swallow might nest forever in high eaves, free from the peril of branches, and the crane might emerge from the dust of its cage to know at last the ease of the carriage.

    Now I wish to compose this letter to present again to you, to express even a fraction of my gratitude and to record in advance my farewell. Yet I know not if this is fitting, so I seek first your direction.

    As for myself: though I possess something of Jiang Wei's courage, I lack Deng Ai's eloquence. Even in formal audience, I would struggle to speak befittingly. So I entrust these words to brush and ink to lay bare what my heart cannot voice. Unable to concern myself with my own worth, I boldly seek your benevolence. Your mind, General, is like a mirror—nothing hidden escapes its sight. My person is but an arrow—I follow only your command. Having troubled you so often, my shame and reverence grow ever deeper. I humbly pray you will regard me with care, from beginning to end.
  footnotes:
    - Choe Chi-won (857-?), known by his courtesy name Gyeonghu, was a Silla scholar-official of the 9th century who studied in Tang China and became one of Korea's greatest classical writers.
    - This letter, addressed to a military commander (將軍), exemplifies the formal Korean-Chinese epistolary style. The General's identity remains implicit, typical of court correspondence.
    - The references to Jiang Wei (姜維) and Deng Ai (鄧艾) are allusions to Three Kingdoms generals—the former famous for bravery, the latter for military strategy but inarticulate speech.
    - The needle and thread (針線) and peg-in-bag (錐) images are classical metaphors for a talented person finally finding their place and opportunity to serve.
    - Choe Chi-won's use of self-deprecating language and classical allusions reflects both Confucian virtue ethics and the Tang-influenced Korean literati tradition of displaying refined learning.
